Are you sure it wasn't an accident?

525
00:23:01,186 --> 00:23:03,833
He couldn't have been aiming at your head.

526
00:23:03,929 --> 00:23:04,993
What he said was...

527
00:23:05,064 --> 00:23:07,928
and I wrote this down
because I wanted to be exact...

528
00:23:08,004 --> 00:23:08,820
"Leave me alone,"

529
00:23:08,868 --> 00:23:12,322
"or I'm going to throw
this stapler at your head."

530
00:23:12,428 --> 00:23:14,016
I-I'm so sorry.

531
00:23:14,089 --> 00:23:16,567
You do know that M.J.
just lost his father, right?

532
00:23:16,637 --> 00:23:19,359
I do. My heart goes out to both of you.

533
00:23:19,450 --> 00:23:21,992
But there is no place for
violence in my classroom,

534
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:24,938
no matter what
the circumstances are at home.

535
00:23:25,058 --> 00:23:26,418
"Circumstances"?

536
00:23:26,539 --> 00:23:28,078
Um...

537
00:23:28,153 --> 00:23:32,112
I mean, it's not like
he just lost his favorite toy

538
00:23:32,151 --> 00:23:33,982
or a pet turtle.

539
00:23:34,067 --> 00:23:36,098
He... lost his dad.

540
00:23:36,177 --> 00:23:39,010
Yes, but if M.J. had thrown
that stapler a little harder,

541
00:23:39,080 --> 00:23:42,044
my grandkids might have lost
their grandmother.

542
00:23:42,857 --> 00:23:44,895
Well, I'm sure that he is sorry.

543
00:23:44,976 --> 00:23:47,773
He isn't. In fact, he said... and I quote...

544
00:23:48,116 --> 00:23:49,485
"Bull's-eye."

545
00:23:49,595 --> 00:23:52,285
I'm considering having him
removed from my class.

546
00:23:52,470 --> 00:23:54,103
Okay. Uh...

547
00:23:55,146 --> 00:23:57,647
What M.J. did was wrong,

548
00:23:57,770 --> 00:24:01,228
but... I'm finding it hard to believe

549
00:24:01,284 --> 00:24:04,301
that a person that spends
so much time with children

550
00:24:04,402 --> 00:24:07,667
could be so oblivious to a child's pain.

551
00:24:07,763 --> 00:24:10,620
I have 20 other children
I need to protect.

552
00:24:10,736 --> 00:24:13,553
And M.J. is a very angry little boy.

553
00:24:13,639 --> 00:24:16,061
Well, of course he's angry.

554
00:24:16,162 --> 00:24:17,324
He's 9,

555
00:24:17,470 --> 00:24:21,236
and one of the most important
and loving people

556
00:24:21,371 --> 00:24:24,310
in his life has just been
ripped away from him,

557
00:24:24,415 --> 00:24:27,119
and now he has to live with the fact

558
00:24:27,197 --> 00:24:29,865
that his father is never coming back.

559
00:24:29,947 --> 00:24:31,176
Inside voices, please.

560
00:24:31,222 --> 00:24:33,138
Oh, to hell with your "Inside voices."

561
00:24:33,229 --> 00:24:35,161
His father is dead.

562
00:24:35,231 --> 00:24:37,753
My husband is dead!

563
00:24:38,928 --> 00:24:42,560
Oh! My foot.

564
00:24:49,165 --> 00:24:51,306
It's her.

565
00:24:56,498 --> 00:24:58,481
Why is everyone looking at me?
Did I do something wrong?

566
00:24:58,553 --> 00:25:00,586
No. No, in fact, we have done nothing

567
00:25:00,647 --> 00:25:03,806
but talk about your shopping skills
for the last 24 hours.

568
00:25:05,002 --> 00:25:05,502
Really?

569
00:25:05,502 --> 00:25:06,677
Yes. We even went back

570
00:25:06,747 --> 00:25:08,796
and watched the security tape
to see it again.

571
00:25:08,966 --> 00:25:11,167
Well, keep the tape. It was my last show.

572
00:25:11,249 --> 00:25:13,798
- What?
- Uh, circumstances have changed.

573
00:25:13,913 --> 00:25:16,992
My shopping days are over.
So just do me a favor.

574
00:25:17,053 --> 00:25:18,712
Wait till I'm gone to restock the boots.

575
00:25:18,727 --> 00:25:20,736
I can't cry again today.

576
00:25:20,781 --> 00:25:23,061
Uh, wait. Wait.

577
00:25:23,182 --> 00:25:25,214
Take care of these for Mrs. Solis

578
00:25:25,291 --> 00:25:27,784
and bring her a glass of champagne.

579
00:25:28,006 --> 00:25:29,264
- Champagne?
- Mm-hmm.

580
00:25:29,292 --> 00:25:30,678
Did you not hear me? I'm broke.

581
00:25:30,907 --> 00:25:32,360
You have no reason to
suck up to me anymore.

582
00:25:32,433 --> 00:25:36,146
Well, I do if I want you to work here.

583
00:25:36,687 --> 00:25:37,188
Huh?

584
00:25:37,188 --> 00:25:40,655
You see, you're like a...
a shopping savant,

585
00:25:40,726 --> 00:25:43,754
and every day, women come in here
with all the money in the world

586
00:25:43,805 --> 00:25:46,033
and no clue what to spend it on.

587
00:25:46,092 --> 00:25:47,029
You could help them.

588
00:25:47,080 --> 00:25:48,675
You mean like a personal shopper job?

589
00:25:48,862 --> 00:25:50,966
No, do not think of it as a job.

590
00:25:51,092 --> 00:25:52,824
For you, my dear, it is a calling.

591
00:25:54,237 --> 00:25:55,055
I don't know.

592
00:25:55,106 --> 00:25:56,899
Employees get a 40% discount.

593
00:25:57,333 --> 00:25:58,765
Hi. Welcome to Cumberly's.

594
00:25:58,822 --> 00:26:01,238
My name's Gabrielle. Can I help you?

595
00:26:13,091 --> 00:26:16,256
I want to thank you
for accepting my apology

596
00:26:16,295 --> 00:26:18,164
and coming over before you left town.

597
00:26:18,875 --> 00:26:20,996
I feel like I haven't had
the appropriate reaction

598
00:26:21,084 --> 00:26:22,191
to this wedding.

599
00:26:22,291 --> 00:26:24,753
No. No, no, you've been wonderful.

600
00:26:24,847 --> 00:26:26,068
Well,

601
00:26:26,150 --> 00:26:30,494
to show you how excited I am that
my little boy is getting married,

602
00:26:30,837 --> 00:26:33,904
I've thrown you
a surprise engagement party.

603
00:26:44,294 --> 00:26:45,799
Mom, what the hell is this?

604
00:26:45,896 --> 00:26:48,024
Oh, I just invited some
of your old friends over

605
00:26:48,095 --> 00:26:49,858
to congratulate you.

606
00:26:49,971 --> 00:26:51,945
Hey, girl. I haven't seen you in ages.

607
00:26:52,039 --> 00:26:54,652
Those shoes are ferosh.

608
00:26:56,868 --> 00:26:58,311
Who's this hag?

609
00:26:58,386 --> 00:27:01,651
This is Andrew's fiancee Mary Beth.

610
00:27:02,416 --> 00:27:04,835
Hi, Mary Beth. I'm Brian with an "I."

611
00:27:04,895 --> 00:27:07,362
This is Bryan with a "Y."

612
00:27:07,690 --> 00:27:10,051
What is this about you getting
married? We need to dish.

613
00:27:10,578 --> 00:27:11,944
Um, uh, sweetie, why don't...

614
00:27:12,035 --> 00:27:13,995
why don't you go in
the kitchen and grab a drink?

615
00:27:17,709 --> 00:27:19,394
I just love those boys.

616
00:27:19,479 --> 00:27:21,630
They used to be here all the time.

617
00:27:22,478 --> 00:27:25,061
So what did you think of Andrew's friends?

618
00:27:25,161 --> 00:27:28,390
They seem sweet and very well-groomed.

619
00:27:28,605 --> 00:27:31,261
Well, yeah, but don't they seem,

620
00:27:31,349 --> 00:27:34,254
I don't know, a little... disco-y?

621
00:27:34,447 --> 00:27:37,668
Mrs. Van de Kamp, I know Andrew's gay.

622
00:27:37,758 --> 00:27:38,903
You do?

623
00:27:38,963 --> 00:27:40,736
We've never actually made love,

624
00:27:40,776 --> 00:27:44,214
and he has a picture of
Michael Phelps next to his bed.

625
00:27:44,282 --> 00:27:46,923
Says it's patriotic, but...

626
00:27:47,439 --> 00:27:49,784
I don't understand.
If you know about him...

627
00:27:49,845 --> 00:27:51,360
You have to understand,

628
00:27:51,426 --> 00:27:52,981
I grew up fat and lonely.

629
00:27:54,353 --> 00:27:55,215
When I lost all the weight,

630
00:27:55,288 --> 00:27:59,315
I thought men would look at me
differently, but they didn't.

631
00:28:00,028 --> 00:28:02,173
I just kind of gave up.

632
00:28:02,289 --> 00:28:03,381
Oh, Mary Beth.

633
00:28:03,419 --> 00:28:06,786
But then I met Andrew. He's sweet, fun,

634
00:28:06,835 --> 00:28:09,230
and I just thought...

635
00:28:09,502 --> 00:28:11,153
I could do a lot worse.

636
00:28:11,233 --> 00:28:14,352
No. No. No. Now you listen to me.

637
00:28:14,689 --> 00:28:18,708
You deserve real romance
and passion in your life.

638
00:28:18,838 --> 00:28:19,827
I know all about this.

639
00:28:19,913 --> 00:28:22,614
I have been with plenty
of men for companionship

640
00:28:22,632 --> 00:28:24,830
when it should've been for love.

641
00:28:24,916 --> 00:28:27,137
The right man for you
is out there somewhere.

642
00:28:27,232 --> 00:28:29,120
You just can't settle.

643
00:28:29,235 --> 00:28:32,233
It's not fair to you or to Andrew.

644
00:28:47,724 --> 00:28:49,873
I think we need to talk.

645
00:28:51,868 --> 00:28:53,319
All right.

646
00:28:57,136 --> 00:29:01,073
Coming! Coming! Coming!

647
00:29:01,117 --> 00:29:02,152
Okay.

648
00:29:02,378 --> 00:29:03,787
Oh, no.

649
00:29:08,587 --> 00:29:09,204
Hey.

650
00:29:09,278 --> 00:29:12,252
Hey. I-I came as soon
as I got your message.

651
00:29:12,322 --> 00:29:13,719
So power's out, huh?

652
00:29:13,779 --> 00:29:14,814
I know. This is so embarrassing.

653
00:29:14,866 --> 00:29:16,952
I just got off the phone
with the electric company,

654
00:29:17,009 --> 00:29:19,069
and it turns out it's a faulty line,

655
00:29:19,129 --> 00:29:21,434
so they're gonna fix it first
thing tomorrow morning.

656
00:29:21,513 --> 00:29:23,248
So you don't need me to
look at anything or...

657
00:29:23,312 --> 00:29:24,882
I'm sorry. I feel terrible dragging you

658
00:29:24,968 --> 00:29:25,582
all the way over here,

659
00:29:25,654 --> 00:29:28,738
so you want something for
your trouble? A drink or...

660
00:29:28,795 --> 00:29:30,929
Nah. No. No. I don't...
I don't want to be in your hair.

661
00:29:30,980 --> 00:29:32,481
No, no. You're not.

662
00:29:32,612 --> 00:29:34,323
Honestly, it's a little scary

663
00:29:34,404 --> 00:29:37,386
being all alone in a dark house.

664
00:29:37,628 --> 00:29:39,808
Hence the hundreds of candles.

665
00:29:40,564 --> 00:29:43,486
Yeah, I did go a little overboard, huh?

666
00:29:44,104 --> 00:29:45,055
What are you cooking?

667
00:29:45,118 --> 00:29:46,938
It smells amazing in here.

668
00:29:47,033 --> 00:29:49,851
Yeah? I'm trying out
a new recipe for the kids.

669
00:29:49,977 --> 00:29:51,804
Beef bourguignon.

670
00:29:51,919 --> 00:29:52,884
But Penny's with Jane

671
00:29:52,986 --> 00:29:55,373
and Parker's having pizza
with the Martindales.

672
00:29:55,471 --> 00:29:57,654
I love beef bourguignon.

673
00:29:58,570 --> 00:30:00,828
Oh, that's right. I totally forgot.

674
00:30:00,916 --> 00:30:03,109
Y-you remember the first time we tried it?

675
00:30:03,110 --> 00:30:05,562
New York. Our second anniversary.

676
00:30:05,563 --> 00:30:08,230
Oh, that must be where I got the idea.

677
00:30:08,231 --> 00:30:10,691
I was just looking at
pictures from that trip.

678
00:30:10,692 --> 00:30:13,047
Oh, yeah? You-you got
out the old photo album?

679
00:30:13,048 --> 00:30:13,995
Yeah.

680
00:30:13,996 --> 00:30:16,360
Oh, ho ho. Man!

681
00:30:16,924 --> 00:30:19,048
Look at us.

682
00:30:19,980 --> 00:30:20,952
Hey.

683
00:30:21,580 --> 00:30:23,880
Why don't you stay for dinner?
I'll make you a plate.

684
00:30:24,380 --> 00:30:25,894
Yeah, I don't know.

685
00:30:25,895 --> 00:30:28,470
Come on. Jane's at the concert.

686
00:30:28,471 --> 00:30:29,594
What would you rather do...

687
00:30:29,595 --> 00:30:33,305
eat a microwave dinner all
alone in your apartment or...

688
00:30:34,350 --> 00:30:35,817
beef bourguignon?

689
00:30:35,981 --> 00:30:36,985
Well...

690
00:30:37,758 --> 00:30:39,945
I hate for it to go to waste.

691
00:30:48,829 --> 00:30:50,636
Well, I hope you're happy.

692
00:30:50,637 --> 00:30:52,914
Mary Beth is on her way back to Wisconsin.

693
00:30:52,915 --> 00:30:54,049
I'm sorry.

694
00:30:54,195 --> 00:30:56,435
Why are you so concerned about her life?

695
00:30:56,436 --> 00:30:58,110
What about me?! I'm your son.

696
00:30:58,111 --> 00:31:00,922
I did this for you.
Can you look me in the eye

697
00:31:00,923 --> 00:31:02,146
and tell me you would've been happy

698
00:31:02,147 --> 00:31:04,591
spending the rest of
your life with that woman?

699
00:31:04,772 --> 00:31:07,983
That marriage really
could have helped me out,

700
00:31:07,987 --> 00:31:10,211
and you have no idea how much help I need.

701
00:31:10,212 --> 00:31:12,128
Why? What is going on?

702
00:31:12,628 --> 00:31:14,350
Where do I start? Um...

703
00:31:15,555 --> 00:31:18,079
Well, I took a loss on
the house that you got me,

704
00:31:19,154 --> 00:31:21,646
I, uh, I lost my job,

705
00:31:21,796 --> 00:31:23,135
can't find a new one.

706
00:31:23,799 --> 00:31:25,972
I have a ton of credit card debt,

707
00:31:26,551 --> 00:31:29,630
and Mary Beth was willing to
help me out with all of that.

708
00:31:29,631 --> 00:31:32,878
Well, so would I. Why didn't
you come to me for help?

709
00:31:32,879 --> 00:31:35,114
Do you know what it feels like
to have to keep running back

710
00:31:35,115 --> 00:31:37,207
to your mother to fix your problems?

711
00:31:37,819 --> 00:31:40,647
My whole life,
you've been propping me up...

712
00:31:40,652 --> 00:31:44,695
when I needed a job, when I was dumped,
when I was drinking.

713
00:31:44,876 --> 00:31:46,262
I'm just... I'm so tired

714
00:31:46,263 --> 00:31:49,311
of you seeing me as a failure.

715
00:31:49,312 --> 00:31:51,462
Andrew, if you would
go through all of this

716
00:31:51,463 --> 00:31:53,270
rather than come to me for help,

717
00:31:53,271 --> 00:31:55,683
then I am the one who's failed.

718
00:31:59,895 --> 00:32:02,515
How about we just agree
that we both failed?

719
00:32:06,039 --> 00:32:07,556
So what are you gonna do now?

720
00:32:07,703 --> 00:32:10,074
I don't know. I had a
pretty good setup there...

721
00:32:10,075 --> 00:32:12,487
a place to live, somebody who needed me,

722
00:32:13,427 --> 00:32:15,338
all the frozen custard I could eat.

723
00:32:15,339 --> 00:32:17,162
Well, I don't have any custard,

724
00:32:17,163 --> 00:32:19,610
but I can offer you a place to stay,

725
00:32:19,611 --> 00:32:23,639
and... someone else who needs you.

726
00:32:26,219 --> 00:32:27,335
All right.

727
00:32:28,315 --> 00:32:30,886
But just until I get
back on my feet again.

728
00:32:36,219 --> 00:32:38,072
Now let's talk about that party.

729
00:32:38,463 --> 00:32:42,753
I could swear I saw Bryan with
a "Y" checking you out.

730
00:32:42,754 --> 00:32:44,718
Ah, well, actually,

731
00:32:44,719 --> 00:32:47,475
I am more into Geoffrey with a "G."

732
00:32:47,476 --> 00:32:49,311
Now that's my gay son.

733
00:32:52,820 --> 00:32:55,086
God, look at all the stuff we're doing.

734
00:32:55,087 --> 00:32:56,490
We used to be interesting.

735
00:32:56,491 --> 00:32:59,590
I know. We-we hiked.
We went to the theater.

736
00:32:59,591 --> 00:33:02,774
We-we took salsa lessons.

737
00:33:02,775 --> 00:33:05,044
And then came the kids.

738
00:33:05,128 --> 00:33:07,779
Ah, fun killers. Huh.

739
00:33:11,800 --> 00:33:12,642
Mmm. This is amazing.

740
00:33:12,643 --> 00:33:14,979
It's even better than that
restaurant in New York.

741
00:33:14,980 --> 00:33:17,039
I don't know. That place was pretty good.

742
00:33:17,697 --> 00:33:18,922
How did we even find it?

743
00:33:18,923 --> 00:33:20,535
- You don't remember?
- Mnh-mnh.

744
00:33:21,019 --> 00:33:23,698
We got caught in that torrential downpour.

745
00:33:23,699 --> 00:33:25,962
We ducked in there to dry off.

746
00:33:25,963 --> 00:33:29,602
Right. And then the owner insisted
on making us a special meal

747
00:33:29,603 --> 00:33:31,760
because we had that newlywed look.

748
00:33:36,479 --> 00:33:38,676
A lot of water under that bridge, huh?

749
00:33:39,985 --> 00:33:42,333
Yeah, but it was a pretty strong bridge.

750
00:33:46,322 --> 00:33:47,804
Look how young we were.

751
00:33:49,105 --> 00:33:50,252
Yeah.

752
00:33:52,177 --> 00:33:55,933
Back then I could actually see
without my reading glasses.

753
00:33:56,113 --> 00:33:58,371
Here you go. Best I can do for light.

754
00:33:58,372 --> 00:33:59,759
Thank you.

755
00:34:05,283 --> 00:34:06,479
Ha ha ha.

756
00:34:06,679 --> 00:34:09,060
I'm glad you kept these.

757
00:34:10,263 --> 00:34:11,843
Good memories, huh?

758
00:34:13,240 --> 00:34:14,308
Yeah.

759
00:34:14,311 --> 00:34:16,131
You know, sometimes you just get...

760
00:34:17,976 --> 00:34:20,787
overwhelmed by work and...

761
00:34:21,864 --> 00:34:23,851
kids and life, and it's just...

762
00:34:24,905 --> 00:34:26,883
so easy to...

763
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:30,180
forget.

764
00:34:30,551 --> 00:34:31,523
Yeah.

765
00:34:33,048 --> 00:34:35,635
Yeah, it is.

766
00:34:37,862 --> 00:34:39,114
I'm on fire.

767
00:34:39,115 --> 00:34:40,582
Oh, my god. Oh, my god! I'on fire!

768
00:34:40,583 --> 00:34:42,835
Oh! Oh, my god! Oh!

769
00:34:48,232 --> 00:34:48,786
Are you okay?

770
00:34:48,787 --> 00:34:50,582
I think I burnt the skin.

771
00:34:50,583 --> 00:34:52,770
Oh, jeez. Let me see.

772
00:34:56,999 --> 00:34:58,899
Oh, it doesn't look so bad.

773
00:34:59,511 --> 00:35:01,363
I thought the power was out.

774
00:35:02,711 --> 00:35:05,363
They must have... fixed it.

775
00:35:05,959 --> 00:35:07,139
You set this up.

776
00:35:07,140 --> 00:35:08,936
You know, in-in my defense, I...

777
00:35:08,937 --> 00:35:10,018
What the hell is going on?

778
00:35:10,019 --> 00:35:12,374
I just wanted to see where we stood,

779
00:35:12,375 --> 00:35:14,374
if there was still anything between us,

780
00:35:14,375 --> 00:35:18,539
if we could find our way back
to those people in the pictures.

781
00:35:18,656 --> 00:35:20,060
By tricking me?

782
00:35:20,191 --> 00:35:22,151
